    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1304686344" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1304686344" />
    <a title="Cari" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10519557-cari"><img alt="Cari" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1569177093p2/10519557.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1304686344?book_show_action=true">Jun 10, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cari" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cari" href="/user/show/10519557-cari">Cari</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10519557-cari?shelf=stand-alone">stand-alone</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10519557-cari?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10519557-cari?shelf=read-on-oyster">read-on-oyster</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10519557-cari?shelf=read-in-2015">read-in-2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1304686344" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7073183218476967111"><i>The Madonnas of Leningrad</i> sounds like a book I would love. It is about an elderly Russian woman with Alzheimers who can not remember details about her current day-to-day life, but is constantly experiencing flashbacks to her teenage years during the Leningrad blockade. I first read about Hitler&apos;s siege of Leningrad and the resulting starvation of thousands of Russian civilians in <i>The Bronze Horseman</i> and was blown away by the suffering that took place during that time. I find the subject so inter</span>
  <span id="freeText7073183218476967111" style="display:none"><i>The Madonnas of Leningrad</i> sounds like a book I would love. It is about an elderly Russian woman with Alzheimers who can not remember details about her current day-to-day life, but is constantly experiencing flashbacks to her teenage years during the Leningrad blockade. I first read about Hitler's siege of Leningrad and the resulting starvation of thousands of Russian civilians in <i>The Bronze Horseman</i> and was blown away by the suffering that took place during that time. I find the subject so interesting (you know I'm a World War II junkie) and began to focus my World War II reads on Stalin's Russia and the Red Army. So, when I saw this book on Oyster, I was really excited, as it featured not only the Leningrad siege-- but also Alzheimers. <br /><br /> I am always very interested in books featuring elderly main characters suffering from dementia, as I take care of these people every day and know how tragic and terrifying it is for them. Despite the fact that it is fiction, reading these types of books allow me to see the disease through the eyes of those experiencing it, rather than through the eyes of the caregiver. Books about Alzheimers usually give great perspective and are usually very emotionally significant reads for me, so again, I was excited to read this book...<br /><br />And then I read it...<br /><br />And I was so disappointed. <br />The writing in <i>The Madonnas of Leningrad</i> made me feel completely disconnected from the characters and storyline. This type of book should make me <b>cry cry cry</b> but I never was able to experience war torn Leningrad through this author's words. It was really unclear what was going on when Marina was having flashbacks. It felt like the present day story would just be interrupted and go into a totally different storyline with no correlation between the two. The only way I really knew what was going on was that I knew that was what the book was supposed to be about. It could have been <b>such a great book</b> if it was written differently! It also felt very incomplete... Neither the flashbacks to World War II nor the present day Alzheimers storyline got a <i>real</i> conclusion. You can't do a book with this type of plot in a way that gives it justice in a meager 256 pages. You just can't. <br /><br />Now, with my complaining out of the way I do want to point out a couple lines in the book that really stood out to me: <br /><br /><i>"No one weeps anymore, or if they do, it is over small things, inconsequential moments that catch them unprepared. What is left that is heartbreaking? Not death; death is ordinary. ...What is heartbreaking is that there is still beauty in the world."</i><br /><br />☆☆</span>
  <a data-text-id="7073183218476967111" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

