    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1927695674" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1927695674" />
    <a title="Elizabeth  Higginbotham " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22019321-elizabeth-higginbotham"><img alt="Elizabeth  Higginbotham " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1376516893p2/22019321.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1927695674?book_show_action=true">Mar 04, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth  Higginbotham " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth  Higginbotham " href="/user/show/22019321-elizabeth-higginbotham">Elizabeth  Higginbotham </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1927695674" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1209801187157328890">The Madonnas of Leningrad is an amazing journey. This non-linear book has us in the past, during WW II in Russia where as young woman, Marina, has to face the challenges of hunger, bombing, and the death of her family members. She is separated from her lover, but their love for each other helps them each survive and they are reunited and eventually come to the USA. We move through time in other chapters that capture the present as the couple, Marina and Dmitri, cope with aging and the wife’s Alz</span>
  <span id="freeText1209801187157328890" style="display:none">The Madonnas of Leningrad is an amazing journey. This non-linear book has us in the past, during WW II in Russia where as young woman, Marina, has to face the challenges of hunger, bombing, and the death of her family members. She is separated from her lover, but their love for each other helps them each survive and they are reunited and eventually come to the USA. We move through time in other chapters that capture the present as the couple, Marina and Dmitri, cope with aging and the wife’s Alzheimer’s disease. The description of the difficulties of surviving the war in St. Petersburg are amazing and horrifying, especially when one thinks of the many people facing war in this era. As she copes with Alzheimer’s, Marina lives much in the past and she becomes more and more removed from the present. She is in crisis at her granddaughter’s wedding, not able to follow the action. This is when her own daughter, Helen, discovers the seriousness of her mother’s condition, but can only accept it and she does as she begins to draw her own mother. Her son, Andrei, born during the war, is trying to get his parents to face their situation, but like many aging people they do not want to leave their home. The detail on how Marina copes with Alzheimer’s is amazing. The writing is compelling as the Heritage is stripped of its treasures; Marina has learned to keep these memories alive as she can describe the many pictures that have been taken out of their frames and stores so that they cannot be destroyed. This vivid world is in her memory and more real than the people who surround her in the present. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1209801187157328890" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

